756,prog45847,"/*Given an integer array, print the length of longest ascending (strictly increasing) subsequence.
For example, for array A = [1, -2, 3, -5, 5], the longest ascending subsequence is [1, 3, 5]. Hence, the output is: 3
Let A[0..n-1] be the input array. Let's create another array MaxTill[0..n-1].
In this array, MaxTill[i] denotes the length of longest ascending subsequence till index i such that A[i] is an element of the longest sequence.
So, MaxTill[i] can be written as
MaxTill[i] = max( max(1+MaxTill[j] where j < i and A[j] < A[i]), 1 )
If there exists j < i and A[j] < A[i] then MaxTill[i] = max(1+MaxTill[j]) where j is all the possible values satisfying j < i and A[j] < A[i]
If such a j does not exist then MaxTill[i] = 1
The length of longest ascending subsequence will be the max of all values in MaxTill[0..n-1]
First line contains size N of the array.
Next line contains N space separated integers giving the contents of the array.
Output the length of longest ascending subsequence.
The array size is smaller than 20.
Each array entry is an integer which fits an int data type.
